      "id": "HOR-024",
      "number": 235,
      "title": "CFPB Operational Dismantling and Funding Leverage [Integrated into REG-001 and REG-007]",
      "full_title": "HOR-024: CFPB Operational Dismantling and Funding Leverage [Integrated into REG-001 and REG-007]",
      "issue_state": "Closed",
      "development_level": "Closed",
      "workflow_status": "Closed",
      "area": "Unassigned",
      "priority": "Unassigned",
      "release_blocker": "Unassigned",
      "last_audit": "Not recorded",
      "next_audit": "Not recorded",
      "canonical_page": "https://github.com/Thorncrag/ARRP/issues/235",
      "issue_url": "https://github.com/Thorncrag/ARRP/issues/235",
      "labels": [
        "kind: horizon"
      ],
      "needs_monitoring": false,
      "created_at": "2026-07-02T18:45:56Z",
      "updated_at": "2026-07-19T16:09:31Z",
      "issue_body_html": "<h2>Final Disposition — Integrated into REG-001 and REG-007<\/h2>\n<p><strong>Decision date:<\/strong> July 10, 2026 <strong>Record finalized:<\/strong> July 14, 2026<\/p>\n<p>HOR-024 was integrated into <a href=\"https://github.com/Thorncrag/ARRP/blob/main/areas/REG/issues/REG-001.md\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">REG-001<\/a> and REG-007 in the <a href=\"https://github.com/Thorncrag/ARRP/blob/main/areas/REG/README.md\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Regulatory Neutrality and Independent Agencies area<\/a>. REG-001 owns the operational-disablement and statutory-duty continuity questions; REG-007 owns independent-funding design. Related enforcement, personnel, oversight, appropriations, records, and public-information questions remain routed to their existing homes.<\/p>\n<p>No separate CFPB proposal was created. This closed issue and the <a href=\"https://github.com/Thorncrag/ARRP/blob/main/framework/logs/HORIZON_SCAN_LOG.md\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Horizon Scan Log<\/a> preserve the permanent intake history. The inactive Project card was removed. The archived intake analysis below is retained for provenance and is superseded by this final disposition.<\/p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Archived Intake Record<\/h2>\n<h2>Horizon Candidate<\/h2>\n<p>ARRP should retain the weakening or attempted dismantling of the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau as a horizon intake item for independent-agency and regulatory-neutrality source development.<\/p>\n<h2>Disposition at Intake<\/h2>\n<p>This did not appear to require a new ARRP area or a separate developed proposal. The strongest home was A-17, especially the operational-disablement work now consolidated in REG-001 and the independent-funding work in REG-007. Secondary overlaps included REG-002 on politicized enforcement or nonenforcement, REG-006 on presidential control of rulemaking and legal positions, CIV-008 on hollowing agency capacity, OVS oversight issues, FUND-003 on agency closure or program nullification through nonspending, and FACT/REC issues if records or public-information access became central.<\/p>\n<h2>Why It Matters<\/h2>\n<p>The CFPB episode may expose a recurring institutional weakness: Congress can create a statutory agency and give it standing funding authority, but an executive hostile to the agency may still try to neutralize it through stop-work orders, closure of facilities, mass personnel actions, refusal to draw available funds, dropped enforcement, contract cancellation, litigation positions, records or website removals, and narrowed public-facing information.<\/p>\n<h2>Initial Source-Development Leads<\/h2>\n<ul><li>AP, stop-work and building-closure reporting: https://apnews.com/article/trump-consumer-protection-cease-1b93c60a773b6b5ee629e769ae6850e9<\/li><li>AP, preliminary injunction blocking dismantling: https://apnews.com/article/trump-consumer-financial-protection-bureau-d091cfb0794813e40098a40e00a6d1c2<\/li><li>Supreme Court, <em>Consumer Financial Protection Bureau v. Community Financial Services Association of America<\/em>, 601 U.S. ___ (2024): https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/23pdf/22-448_o7jp.pdf<\/li><li>Supreme Court, <em>Seila Law LLC v. Consumer Financial Protection Bureau<\/em>, 591 U.S. ___ (2020): https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/19pdf/19-7_n6io.pdf<\/li><li>Guardian source-development lead on CFPB website removals and public-information access: https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/ng-interactive/2026/jun/04/trump-administration-consumer-financial-protection-bureau<\/li><\/ul>\n<h2>Development Questions at Intake<\/h2>\n<ul><li>Should the existing regulatory proposals remain separate, or should A-17 eventually consolidate agency dismantling, funding refusal, enforcement nullification, and records/public-access safeguards?<\/li><li>What statutory remedies would survive <em>Seila Law<\/em> and later unitary-executive doctrine while still preventing functional repeal of a congressionally created agency?<\/li><li>Could Congress require minimum operational capacity, mandatory complaint intake, minimum supervision/enforcement functions, continuity of public guidance and records, congressional notice, GAO certification, or expedited review when an agency is placed into de facto shutdown?<\/li><li>How should the proposal distinguish lawful policy reprioritization from unlawful functional nullification of a statutory mission?<\/li><\/ul>\n<h2>Status at Intake<\/h2>\n<p>Active horizon intake. Integrate into the relevant regulatory-neutrality proposals unless later review shows a distinct CFPB or consumer-financial-protection proposal is warranted.<\/p>",
