        "original_concern": "Executive use of sanctions, visa restrictions, and diplomatic pressure to isolate or dismantle the International Criminal Court despite Congress having enacted a narrower noncooperation framework and not enacted H.R. 23's specific sanctions mandate.",
        "decision": "Integrated into and used to develop existing EMERG-003; static HOR ID and closed GitHub issue #250 retained as the permanent horizon intake record.",
        "integrated_into": "EMERG-003 in A-10; boundary cross-reference to HOR-026 for withdrawal from institutions the United States affirmatively joined or Congress approved.",
        "rationale": "The political merits of ICC membership, jurisdiction, recognition, or cooperation are outside ARRP. The repairable defect is narrower and generalizable: Executive Order 14203 used IEEPA, the NEA, and immigration delegations to establish property and entry sanctions after Congress considered but did not enact a specific sanctions bill. ASPA supplies substantial noncooperation policy but not a general property-blocking mandate, and it preserves limited Ukraine-related assistance. EMERG-003 is the existing substantive-authority home; creating an ICC-specific proposal would fragment the emergency-powers defect.",
        "follow_up": "Conduct T1 review of the first statutory draft, including direct-nexus language, the specific-authorization rule, independently sanctionable conduct, INA coordination, D.D.C. review, classified records, transition relief, and budget implementation. Revisit the horizon disposition only if later action reveals a distinct defect not addressable through emergency-authority limits or HOR-026's international-commitment framework.",
