      "needs_monitoring": true,
      "created_at": "2026-07-16T21:36:24Z",
      "updated_at": "2026-07-20T21:47:42Z",
      "issue_body_html": "<h2>Canonical Project Page<\/h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://github.com/Thorncrag/ARRP/blob/main/framework/logs/HORIZON_SCAN_LOG.md\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Horizon Scan Log<\/a><\/li><li><a href=\"https://github.com/Thorncrag/ARRP/blob/main/areas/RIGHTS/README.md\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Provisional civil-rights area<\/a><\/li><li>Horizon ID: <code>HOR-033<\/code><\/li><li>Preliminary intake provenance: <code>INTAKE-GAP-002<\/code><\/li><\/ul>\n<h2>Workflow Purpose<\/h2>\n<p>This GitHub issue is the public workflow wrapper for an ARRP Horizon candidate concerning whether existing accessibility duties governing presidential communications have a sufficiently explicit and timely enforcement route. The repository remains the authoritative substantive record.<\/p>\n<h2>Institutional Question<\/h2>\n<p>Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act supplies an existing accessibility duty, and district courts have ordered ASL access for specified White House briefings. The unresolved question is narrower: whether an affected person has a sufficiently clear cause of action and timely remedy when presidential or White House communications exclude people with disabilities.<\/p>\n<h2>Related Communications Issue<\/h2>\n<p>The candidate is adjacent to HOR-027 because a President may use social media or another nontraditional channel for consequential official communications. HOR-027 owns official publication, authentication, preservation, and channel governance. This candidate asks whether whatever channel is used provides legally sufficient disability access and an effective enforcement mechanism. The two concerns should be cross-checked without being automatically merged.<\/p>\n<h2>Scope and Counterargument<\/h2>\n<p>Violation of an already enforceable duty is not itself a new institutional defect. Ordinary injunctive litigation may demonstrate that the existing system works, particularly if appellate review confirms the private enforcement route. The candidate should advance only if the pending litigation exposes a recurring enforcement, coverage, or timeliness gap.<\/p>\n<h2>Monitoring Status and Next Step<\/h2>\n<p>Monitor the D.C. Circuit treatment of the section 504 cause-of-action question. Source-develop coverage of presidential briefings, social-media communications, emergency announcements, captions, transcripts, ASL interpretation, and other accessibility methods; identify whether delayed relief creates irreparable loss of contemporaneous access; and test overlap with RIGHTS-001, JUD-001, JUD-005, FACT-001, PRESS-001, and HOR-027 before making an admission recommendation.<\/p>",
