      "issue_body_html": "<h2>Horizon candidate<\/h2>\n<p><strong>Horizon provenance:<\/strong> HOR-038<\/p>\n<h2>Why this is deferred<\/h2>\n<p>This candidate is deferred because the final rules&#x27; operative scope, implementation record, and judicial posture are not yet developed enough to establish a distinct institutional weakness or a fitted remedy. Reconsider it when a stated trigger occurs.<\/p>\n<p><strong>Current disposition:<\/strong> Deferred candidate. This record does not admit a proposal or recommend a preferred environmental-policy outcome.<\/p>\n<h2>Concern<\/h2>\n<p>On July 17, 2026, the Department of the Interior announced finalized changes to Fish and Wildlife Service regulations under ESA sections 4(d) and 4(b)(2), including repeal of the blanket threatened-species rule and a revised critical-habitat exclusion procedure. The candidate asks whether the final rules, their implementation, or review procedures reveal a durable statutory-boundary or timely-remedy weakness.<\/p>\n<p>The inquiry must preserve a key statutory distinction: ESA listing determinations are made solely on the best scientific and commercial data available, while critical-habitat designation may consider economic, national-security, and other relevant impacts, with an extinction safeguard. A policy disagreement with either exercise of delegated discretion is not enough.<\/p>\n<h2>Reconsideration triggers<\/h2>\n<p>Reassess this candidate when any of the following occurs:<\/p>\n<ol><li>the final Federal Register text or implementing guidance clarifies the rules&#x27; operative scope;<\/li><li>a court issues a merits or controlling threshold ruling on the 2026 rules;<\/li><li>an ESA listing, delisting, or critical-habitat decision applies economic considerations in a way that may conflict with the statute&#x27;s science-only listing standard; or<\/li><li>evidence shows difficult-to-repair loss before ordinary administrative or judicial review can operate.<\/li><\/ol>\n<h2>Preliminary scope and overlap check<\/h2>\n<p>No existing ARRP proposal cleanly owns the statutory boundary between delegated ESA discretion and a potential displacement of congressionally prescribed decision criteria. This candidate remains provisionally cross-cutting, rather than being assigned to a substantive proposal area, while the rule text and litigation record develop. It should be retired if the final materials remain within the discretion Congress provided and ordinary review appears adequate.<\/p>\n<h2>Initial sources<\/h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://www.doi.gov/node/67431\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Department of the Interior announcement (July 17, 2026)<\/a><\/li><li><a href=\"https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title16-section1533&amp;num=0&amp;edition=prelim\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">16 U.S.C. § 1533<\/a><\/li><\/ul>\n<h2>Next step<\/h2>\n<p>Reconsider the candidate when a defined trigger occurs; do not draft legislation unless a distinct, generalizable institutional weakness is established.<\/p>",
