      "id": "HOR-045",
      "number": 311,
      "title": "Immigration-Enforcement Vehicle-Stop Safeguards",
      "full_title": "HOR-045: Immigration-Enforcement Vehicle-Stop Safeguards",
      "issue_state": "Open",
      "development_level": "Candidate",
      "workflow_status": "Deferred",
      "area": "DOM",
      "priority": "Parked",
      "release_blocker": "Later",
      "last_audit": "Horizon intake and deferral (2026-07-19)",
      "next_audit": "Monitor Maine findings and research other DHS immigration vehicle-stop incidents.",
      "canonical_page": "https://github.com/Thorncrag/ARRP/issues/311",
      "issue_url": "https://github.com/Thorncrag/ARRP/issues/311",
      "labels": [
        "kind: horizon"
      ],
      "needs_monitoring": false,
      "created_at": "2026-07-19T19:28:02Z",
      "updated_at": "2026-07-23T10:53:00Z",
      "issue_body_html": "<h2>Canonical Project Page<\/h2>\n<ul><li>Horizon ID: <code>HOR-045<\/code><\/li><\/ul>\n<h2>Current disposition<\/h2>\n<p><strong>Deferred proposed candidate.<\/strong> This record does not conclude that the Biddeford stop or shooting was unlawful. It remains open while the project follows the Maine investigation and determines whether immigration-enforcement vehicle stops reveal a broader, distinct institutional weakness.<\/p>\n<h2>Why this is deferred<\/h2>\n<p>Although incident comparison, source development, and preliminary drafting could proceed now, ARRP is affirmatively postponing further candidate development because the incomplete investigative record, uncertain stop-level facts, and unsettled nationwide policy posture make a remedy premature. Proceeding now could mistake a disputed encounter for an established recurring institutional defect or duplicate safeguards already operating under existing law and policy.<\/p>\n<h2>Institutional question<\/h2>\n<p>Federal immigration officers may stop vehicles to enforce federal law, but they do not ordinarily possess general authority to enforce state and local traffic codes. The candidate asks whether existing law and policy provide adequate safeguards for:<\/p>\n<ul><li>a particularized basis to stop a vehicle or its occupants;<\/li><li>verification when a person or vehicle is not the intended target;<\/li><li>contemporaneous documentation of the facts supporting the stop;<\/li><li>identification, signaling, de-escalation, and safe-stop procedures; and<\/li><li>public reporting sufficient to identify mistaken-target, no-arrest, pursuit, collision, and force patterns.<\/li><\/ul>\n<p>The inquiry is neutral as to immigration policy and individual enforcement outcomes. A mistaken target, disputed shooting, or troubling result does not itself establish that the initial stop lacked lawful justification.<\/p>\n<h2>Current manifestation<\/h2>\n<p>On July 13, 2026, ICE officers conducting targeted surveillance at the last known address of another person attempted to stop a vehicle driven by Johan Sebastián Durán Guerrero in Biddeford, Maine. Durán Guerrero was not the operation&#x27;s intended target, and an ICE officer fatally shot him during the encounter. Public reporting and official statements do not yet establish the complete pre-stop factual basis, what officers knew about Durán Guerrero before initiating the stop, or the final findings concerning the shooting.<\/p>\n<p>The incident followed a July 7 fatal ICE vehicle-stop encounter in Houston involving another person who was reportedly not the intended target. The Department briefly directed officers to suspend most vehicle stops before that direction was reversed. Those events make the broader practice appropriate for structured review, but the available record is not yet sufficient to support an independent proposal.<\/p>\n<h2>Existing safeguards and unresolved gap<\/h2>\n<p>The Fourth Amendment permits an investigative vehicle stop only when officers possess reasonable suspicion grounded in specific, articulable facts. In the immigration context, <em>United States v. Brignoni-Ponce<\/em> holds that apparent ancestry alone is insufficient. <a href=\"https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-8/part-287/section-287.8\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">8 C.F.R. § 287.8<\/a> likewise requires reasonable suspicion for brief immigration questioning and probable cause for a warrantless arrest.<\/p>\n<p>A 2022 ICE vehicle-stop policy issued through the <em>Castañon Nava<\/em> settlement stated that ICE officers lack federal authority to enforce state or local traffic laws and required documentation of the facts supporting reasonable suspicion. That policy is an important comparator, but its current nationwide status and implementation require verification.<\/p>\n<p>The possible institutional defect is therefore not the absence of any legal standard. It is whether the governing standards are sufficiently durable, operationalized, documented, reviewable, and measurable to deter or reveal stops based on mistaken identity, weak association with a surveilled location, or impermissible generalizations.<\/p>\n<h2>Existing ARRP coverage<\/h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/Thorncrag/ARRP/blob/main/areas/DOM/issues/DOM-005.md\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">DOM-005<\/a> addresses preservation and state access to evidence after a critical federal-law-enforcement incident. The DOM-005 proposal issue also carries <code>needs: monitoring<\/code> for the Maine investigation&#x27;s evidence-access posture. This candidate is distinct only to the extent it concerns the prospective authority, verification, documentation, reporting, and safety rules governing immigration-enforcement vehicle stops before force occurs.<\/p>\n<h2>Reconsideration conditions<\/h2>\n<p>Reconsider the deferral when one or more of the following occurs:<\/p>\n<ol><li>the Maine Attorney General, DHS Inspector General, FBI, or another responsible body releases findings, records, a charging decision, or a jurisdictional determination concerning the Biddeford stop and shooting;<\/li><li>litigation produces a ruling or factual record concerning the basis for the stop, identification of the occupants, or applicable federal authority;<\/li><li>DHS or ICE issues, rescinds, or materially revises vehicle-stop, target-verification, signaling, pursuit, documentation, body-camera, or use-of-force policy;<\/li><li>a structured review identifies additional DHS immigration-enforcement vehicle stops involving mistaken targets, non-target occupants, disputed stop authority, collision, injury, or force; or<\/li><li>official records clarify what stop-level data DHS collects, retains, audits, and publishes, and how that practice compares with state and local traffic-stop reporting systems.<\/li><\/ol>\n<h2>Initial sources<\/h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://www1.maine.gov/ag/news-and-library/press-releases/federal-law-enforcement-fatal-use-deadly-force-biddeford-maine-july\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Maine Attorney General statement on the Biddeford investigation<\/a><\/li><li><a href=\"https://apnews.com/article/73681fcf59fceb8b43b198ccaec554d3\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Associated Press report on the Maine and Houston vehicle-stop shootings and temporary policy response<\/a><\/li><li><a href=\"https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/USREPORTS-422/pdf/USREPORTS-422-873.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><em>United States v. Brignoni-Ponce<\/em>, 422 U.S. 873 (1975)<\/a><\/li><li><a href=\"https://www.ice.gov/doclib/legalNotice/220527castanonSettlement_attA.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">ICE vehicle-stop policy issued through the <em>Castañon Nava<\/em> settlement<\/a><\/li><\/ul>\n<h2>Next step<\/h2>\n<p>Keep the candidate deferred while monitoring the Maine matter. In parallel with future candidate review, build a representative incident and policy comparison sufficient to determine whether the concern is recurring, whether existing remedies operate adequately, and whether the proper disposition is admission, merger into an existing proposal, or retirement.<\/p>",
